TY  - JOUR
T1  - Cooperation, Opportunism, and the Invisible Hand: Implications for Transaction Cost Theory
AU  - Hill, Charles W. L.
Y1  - 1990/07/01
PY  - 1990
DA  - 1990/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1990.4309111
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1990.4309111
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 500
EP  - 513
VL  - 15
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Transaction cost theorists have generally neglected to consider the implications that the invisible hand of the market mechanism can have for the risk of opportunism. In the long run, the invisible hand deletes actors whose behaviors are habitually opportunistic. Consequently, as markets move toward the state of competitive equilibrium, the risk of opportunism will be low, even for transactions supported by specific asset investments. Therefore, in many contexts the transaction cost rationale for internalization has been overstated.
AB  - Transaction cost theorists have generally neglected to consider the implications that the invisible hand of the market mechanism can have for the risk of opportunism. In the long run, the invisible hand deletes actors whose behaviors are habitually opportunistic. Consequently, as markets move toward the state of competitive equilibrium, the risk of opportunism will be low, even for transactions supported by specific asset investments. Therefore, in many contexts the transaction cost rationale for internalization has been overstated.
